{"title_page": "Necdet \u015eent\u00fcrk", "text_new": "{{short description|Turkish footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Necdet \u015eent\u00fcrk\n|image          = \n|caption        = \n|fullname       = \n|birth_date     = 1928\n|birth_place    = [[Sivas]], Turkey\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|nationalteam1  = [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]]\n}}\n\n'''Necdet \u015eent\u00fcrk''' (born 1928) was a Turkish [[association football|footballer]]. He competed in the [[Football at the 1952 Summer Olympics|men's tournament]] at the [[1952 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/se/necdet-senturk-1.html |title=Necdet \u015eent\u00fcrk Olympic Results |accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Senturk, Necdet}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:Possibly living people]]\n[[Category:Turkish footballers]]\n[[Category:Turkey international footballers]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 1952 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Sivas]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n{{Turkey-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Turkish footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Necdet \u015eent\u00fcrk\n|image          = \n|caption        = \n|fullname       = \n|birth_date     = 1928\n|birth_place    = [[Sivas]], Turkey\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|nationalteam1  = [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]]\n}}\n\n'''Necdet \u015eent\u00fcrk''' (born 1928) was a Turkish [[association football|footballer]]. He competed in the [[Football at the 1952 Summer Olympics|men's tournament]] at the [[1952 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/se/necdet-senturk-1.html |title=Necdet \u015eent\u00fcrk Olympic Results |accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Senturk, Necdet}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:Possibly living people]]\n[[Category:Turkish footballers]]\n[[Category:Turkey international footballers]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 1952 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Sivas]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n{{Turkey-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Necdet_%C5%9Eent%C3%BCrk"}
{"title_page": "Belle Davis", "text_new": "{{Infobox Person\n| name               = Belle Davis\n| image              = Belle Davis once-billed-as-americas-greatest-coon-cantatrice-of-the-century.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Belle Davis\n| other_names        = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = April 28, 1874\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago]]\n| death_date         = 1938\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n| education          = \n| occupation         = singer and dance director\n| employer           = \n| known_for          = \n| spouse             = [[Eddie Whaley]]\n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| website            = \n| signature          = \n| footnotes          = \n| residence          = \n| religion           = \n}}\n\n'''Belle Davis''' (April 28, 1874 \u2013 1938) was an [[African American]] choreographer, dancer and singer who became famous in the UK before the first world war. She was in a group called the \"Octoroons\" in America and moved to Britain in 1902 where she toured accompanied by young African American boys. She has been said to be the first Black woman to make a recording.\n\n== Life ==\nDavis was born in 1874 in [[Chicago]] (although some say New Orleans<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://eastendwomensmuseum.org/blog/1049|title=Belle Davis, music hall star and choreographer|website=East End Women's Museum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>). She was light skinned and she was encourage to darken her skin so that she would fit the stereotype of a black entertainer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Lotz|first=Rainer E|date=1994|title=Belle Davis and Her Piccaninnies: a Preliminary Bio-, Disco-, and Filmography|url=http://www.arsc-audio.org/journals/v25/v25n2p178-191.pdf|journal=ARSC Journal|volume=XXV|pages=179\u2013|via=}}</ref>\n\nShe was in a group called the \"Octoroons\" in America and She moved to Britain in 1901. She was said to be licensed by the US government to bring child performers to Britain. Some were known to exploit orphans in this way but Davis was noted for her role as their guardian.<ref name=\":1\" />\n[[File:Belle Davis and her pickchicks.png|left|thumb|Belle Davis and \"her pickchicks\"]]\nDavis was appearing at venues on the [[Hackney Empire|Empire Theatre]] circuit later that year. She was a soprano and her singing was of melodies and her appearance was stately and she had handsome promotional pictures. She appeared with two, sometimes four, African American boys who would add dances and comedy to her songs. Two of the boys, both then under ten years old, Irving \"Sneeze\" Williams and Sonny Jones went on to have their own careers as musicians.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nShe has been said to be the first Black woman to make a recording. On 24 January  1902 she made a recording of \"The Honeysuckle and the Bee\" under the name of \"Belle Davis and her Piccaninnies\". They were back the following month to record \"The Rainbow Coon\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TBB0Jh4QlOcC&pg=PA23&lpg=PA23&dq=Irving+'Sneeze'+Williams#v=onepage|title=Black Recording Artists, 1877-1926: An Annotated Discography|date=2012-12-18|page=23|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-0085-7|language=en}}</ref>\n\nDavis would tour with this act visiting many of the major cities in England.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite ODNB|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-64723;jsessionid=B06194C267F6756D09A4E47A458ADE17|title=Davis, Belle (b. 1874, d. in or after 1938), dancer and singer|year=2004|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/64723|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> In 1906 she and her three dancers were interviewed with the comment that one was like \"the nigger-boy in children's picture books\". The following year they were in Germany where two films were made and they survived.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Green|first=Jeffrey|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZfQrBgAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&dq=inauthor:%22Jeffrey%20Green%22&pg=PP1#v=onepage|title=Black Edwardians: Black People in Britain 1901-1914|page=82|date=2012-11-12|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-31823-8|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1925 she was the choreographer at the \"[[Casino de Paris]]\" Music Hall. Here she recruited performers and arranged the dancing until 1929.<ref name=\":0\" /> During this time she returned to London to her house in Holborn where she recruited five dancers including the tap dancer [[Josie Woods]]. They were called the \"Magnolia Blossoms\" and they were taken back to Paris.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/josie-woods-tap-dancing-star-of-music-hall-906487.html|title=Josie Woods: Tap-dancing star of music hall|date=2008-08-23|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nDavis left Europe and returned to America in 1938.<ref name=\":2\" /> No further details are known.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Belle}}\n[[Category:1874 births]]\n[[Category:1938 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Dancers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Person\n| name               = Belle Davis\n| image              = Belle Davis once-billed-as-americas-greatest-coon-cantatrice-of-the-century.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Belle Davis\n| other_names        = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = April 28, 1874\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago]]\n| death_date         = 1938\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n| education          = \n| occupation         = singer and dance director\n| employer           = \n| known_for          = \n| spouse             = [[Eddie Whaley]]\n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| website            = \n| signature          = \n| footnotes          = \n| residence          = \n| religion           = \n}}\n\n'''Belle Davis''' (April 28, 1874 \u2013 1938) was an [[African American]] choreographer, dancer and singer who became famous in the UK before the first world war. She was in a group called the \"Octoroons\" in America and moved to Britain in 1902 where she toured accompanied by young African American boys. She has been said to be the first Black woman to make a recording.\n\n== Life ==\nDavis was born in 1874 in [[Chicago]] (although some say New Orleans<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://eastendwomensmuseum.org/blog/1049|title=Belle Davis, music hall star and choreographer|website=East End Women's Museum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>). She was light skinned and she was encourage to darken her skin so that she would fit the stereotype of a black entertainer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Lotz|first=Rainer E|date=1994|title=Belle Davis and Her Piccaninnies: a Preliminary Bio-, Disco-, and Filmography|url=http://www.arsc-audio.org/journals/v25/v25n2p178-191.pdf|journal=ARSC Journal|volume=XXV|pages=179\u2013|via=}}</ref>\n\nShe was in a group called the \"Octoroons\" in America and She moved to Britain in 1901. She was said to be licensed by the US government to bring child performers to Britain. Some were known to exploit orphans in this way but Davis was noted for her role as their guardian.<ref name=\":1\" />\n[[File:Belle Davis and her pickchicks.png|left|thumb|Belle Davis and \"her pickchicks\"]]\nDavis was appearing at venues on the [[Hackney Empire|Empire Theatre]] circuit later that year. She was a soprano and her singing was of melodies and her appearance was stately and she had handsome promotional pictures. She appeared with two, sometimes four, African American boys who would add dances and comedy to her songs. Two of the boys, both then under ten years old, Irving \"Sneeze\" Williams and Sonny Jones went on to have their own careers as musicians.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nShe has been said to be the first Black woman to make a recording. On 24 January  1902 she made a recording of \"The Honeysuckle and the Bee\" under the name of \"Belle Davis and her Piccaninnies\". They were back the following month to record \"The Rainbow Coon\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TBB0Jh4QlOcC&pg=PA23&lpg=PA23&dq=Irving+'Sneeze'+Williams#v=onepage|title=Black Recording Artists, 1877-1926: An Annotated Discography|date=2012-12-18|page=23|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-0085-7|language=en}}</ref>\n\nDavis would tour with this act visiting many of the major cities in England.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite ODNB|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-64723;jsessionid=B06194C267F6756D09A4E47A458ADE17|title=Davis, Belle (b. 1874, d. in or after 1938), dancer and singer|year=2004|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/64723|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> In 1906 she and her three dancers were interviewed with the comment that one was like \"the nigger-boy in children's picture books\". The following year they were in Germany where two films were made and they survived.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Green|first=Jeffrey|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZfQrBgAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&dq=inauthor:%22Jeffrey%20Green%22&pg=PP1#v=onepage|title=Black Edwardians: Black People in Britain 1901-1914|page=82|date=2012-11-12|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-31823-8|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1925 she was the choreographer at the \"[[Casino de Paris]]\" Music Hall. Here she recruited performers and arranged the dancing until 1929.<ref name=\":0\" /> During this time she returned to London to house in Holborn where she recruited five dancers including the tap dancer [[Josie Woods]]. They were called the \"Magnolia Blossoms\" and they were taken back to Paris.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/josie-woods-tap-dancing-star-of-music-hall-906487.html|title=Josie Woods: Tap-dancing star of music hall|date=2008-08-23|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nDavis left Europe and returned to America in 1938.<ref name=\":2\" /> No further details are known.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Belle}}\n[[Category:1874 births]]\n[[Category:1938 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Dancers]]\n", "name_user": "Victuallers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:m", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belle_Davis"}
{"title_page": "The Platform (film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|2019 Spanish science fiction film by Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Platform\n| film name      = ''El Valiente''\n| image          = The Platform poster.jpg\n| caption        = Promotional release poster\n| director       = [[Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n*David Desola\n*Pedro Rivero\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Iv\u00e1n Massagu\u00e9]]\n*Zorion Eguileor\n*[[Antonia San Juan]]\n*[[Emilio Buale Coka]]\n*Alexandra Masangkay\n}}\n| music          = Aranzazu Calleja\n| cinematography = Jon D. Dom\u00ednguez\n| editing        = Haritz Zubillaga<br />Elena Ruiz\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n*Basque Films\n*Mr. Miyagi Films\n*Plataforma La Pel\u00edcula A.I.E\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Netflix]]\n| released       = {{Nowrap|{{film date|2019|09|06|df=y|[[2019 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2020|03|20|Netflix}}}}\n| runtime        = 94 minutes\n| country        = Spain\n| language       = Spanish\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''The Platform''''' ({{lang-es|El hoyo}}, {{Translation|''The Hole''}}) is a Spanish [[science fiction film|science fiction]] [[horror film|horror]]-[[thriller film|thriller]] film, directed by [[Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia]] and released in 2019.<ref name=nicholson>Amy Nicholson, [https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/the-platform-review-1203330373/ \"Toronto Film Review: 'The Platform'\"]. ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', 10 September 2019.</ref> The film is set in a large, tower-style \"Vertical Self-Management Center\" where the residents, who are periodically switched at random between its 300+ floors, are fed by a platform, initially filled with food, that gradually descends through the levels. It is a system bound to cause conflict, as inmates at the top levels can eat as much as they can, leaving increasingly little for those below.<ref name=nicholson/>\n\nThe film's cast includes [[Iv\u00e1n Massagu\u00e9]], [[Antonia San Juan]], Zorion Eguileor, [[Emilio Buale Coka]] and Alexandra Masangkay.<ref name=nicholson/>\n\nThe film premiered at the [[2019 Toronto International Film Festival]], where it won the [[Toronto International Film Festival People's Choice Award: Midnight Madness|People's Choice Award for Midnight Madness]].<ref>Jessica Wong, [https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/tiff19-awards-1.5284085 \"TIFF 2019: Jojo Rabbit captures TIFF People's Choice Award\"]. [[CBC News]], 15 September 2019.</ref> At TIFF, the film also secured a worldwide streaming deal with [[Netflix]].<ref>Jeremy Kay, [https://www.screendaily.com/news/netflix-takes-world-on-tiff-midnight-madness-hit-the-platform/5142804.article \"Netflix takes world on TIFF Midnight Madness hit 'The Platform'\"]. ''[[Screen Daily]]'', 10 September 2019.</ref> It was released on the streaming service on 20 March 2020.\n\n==Plot==\nGoreng awakes in a concrete cell marked with the number 48. His roommate, Trimagasi, explains that they are in a tower-style facility in which food is delivered via a platform that travels from the top, stopping for a fixed period on each floor. Those on lower levels are able to eat only what those at the top leave them, and they cannot hoard food (the cell is heated or cooled to fatal levels if food is kept). Every month, people are randomly reassigned to a new level. Each resident is allowed to bring one item in with them, Goreng choosing a copy of ''[[Don Quixote]]'', and Trimagasi a self-sharpening knife called the Samurai Plus. \n\nOne day, a bloodied woman named Miharu rides down on the platform, and Trimagasi explains that she descends the pit every month in search of her child. Goreng sees her being attacked by the two people on the level below, and he considers jumping down to help her, but she kills them both and rides the platform down again.\n\nAs they talk, it is revealed that Goreng volunteered to spend six months in the \"Vertical Self-Management Center\" in exchange for a diploma, and Trimagasi is serving a year-long sentence for manslaughter. Over the month, they become friendly, but on the day of the room shuffle, Goreng wakes up tied to the bed. They have been reassigned to level 171, where the platform is expected to be empty of food when it arrives. Trimagasi explains that he plans to cut strips of Goreng's flesh to sustain them both, but only in moderate amounts so he doesn't bleed out. On the eighth day, Trimagasi cuts into Goreng's leg but is attacked by Miharu as she comes down the platform. She frees Goreng and he kills Trimagasi. Miharu cuts some of Trimagasi's flesh, feeding Goreng and eating some herself before continuing down.\n\nThe following month, Goreng awakes on level 33 with a woman, Imoguiri, as a cellmate. The only thing she brought with her was her dog. Goreng recognizes her as the Administration official who interviewed him before sending him to the cells. She tells Goreng that she believes there are 200 floors. She says she was unaware of the horrible conditions and volunteered to try to fix things when she was diagnosed with terminal cancer. Imoguiri rations her food and attempts to convince those below to do so as well, but they ignore her until Goreng threatens to defecate in their food.\n\nGoreng encounters Miharu once again as she rides down on the platform but she appears critically injured, presumably from being in a fight on the higher levels. Goreng and Imoguiri grab her off the platform and tend to her wounds. Goreng explains to Imoguiri about Miharu's search for her child, but Imoguiri says nobody under the age of 16 is allowed into the facility and says Miharu entered alone. \n\nGoreng awakens to see Miharu and Imoguiri in a standoff, as Miharu has eaten Imoguiri's dog.  Goreng awakens the following month on level 202 and finds that Imoguiri has hanged herself. Goreng eats her flesh to survive, experiencing hallucinations of her and Trimagasi instructing him to do so. He then awakens the following month on level 6. His roommate, Baharat, attempts to climb up through the upper level with the help of those above using a rope he brought into the pit. The couple living on the level above first help him, but end up defecating in his face, and pushing him back down. Estimating that there are around 250 levels, Goreng makes a plan to ride the platform down, rationing the food so all get a share, and convinces Baharat to go with him.\n\nAs they descend, they hand out portions to the prisoners, attacking those who refuse to cooperate. Going down, they encounter Miharu fighting two other residents and try to help her, but she is killed, and both men are injured. Goreng and Baharat continue to descend, eventually passing level 250 and reaching level 333 where the platform stops. Goreng notices a child hiding under the bed, and assumes it is Miharu's son. He gets off the platform, followed hesitantly by Baharat, only to have the platform continue downward, leaving them behind. They then discover the child is actually a girl, who turns out to be Miharu's  daughter. Despite Baharat's reluctance, they feed her an untouched [[panna cotta]] they had been saving as a \"message\" for the Administrators at the top. \n\nGoreng passes out and dreams of Baharat telling him that \"the girl is the message.\" The next day, Goreng finds Baharat dead after succumbing to his injuries, and takes the child with him when the platform arrives; they descend to the bottom of the pit where he once again sees Trimagasi, who tells him that \"the message requires no bearer.\" Goreng gets off the platform and walks away with Trimagasi, both turning to watch as the girl is transported upwards.\n\n== Cast==\n[[File:El hoyo prentsaurrekoa rueda de prensa.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Cast and crew members at a press conference in October 2019.]]\n* [[Iv\u00e1n Massagu\u00e9]] as ''Goreng'', named after ''[[:wiktionary:goreng|gor\u00e8ng]]'', which means \"fried\" in Malay/Indonesian.\n* Zorion Eguileor ([[:eu:Zorion_Egileor|eu]]) as ''Trimagasi'', named after terima kasih, which stands for \"thank you\" in Malay/Indonesian language\n* [[Antonia San Juan]] as ''Imoguiri'', named after ''[[Imogiri]]'', a royal graveyard in Indonesia. \n* [[Emilio Buale Coka]] as ''Baharat'', named after ''[[baharat]]'', a spice blend used in Turkish and Greek cuisine.\n* Alexandra Masangkay as ''Miharu'' \n* Eric L. Goode as ''Sr. Brambang'', named after ''[[shallot|brambang]]'', a shallot.\n\n==Production==\nGalder Gaztelu-Urrutia says the film's key message is that \"...humanity will have to move towards the fair [[distribution of wealth]]\", with an exploration of the importance of individual initiative in driving political change that critiques both [[capitalism]] and \"[[Socialism|socialist systems]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cineuropa.org/en/interview/379967 |title=Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia \u2022 Director of The Platform |last= Rivera|first= Alfonso|date=16 October 2020 |website= cineuropa.org|publisher= Cineuropa|access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> The film script is based on a theatre script by [[David Desola]] and [[Pedro Rivero]], to which more action and physical elements were added to make it more suitable for a film.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cineuropa.org/en/interview/379967 |title=Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia \u2022 Director of The Platform |last= Rivera|first= Alfonso|date=16 October 2020 |website= cineuropa.org|publisher= Cineuropa|access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> \"Extensive\" rewriting was required to convert the unproduced theater script into a film script. The director said it was a \"torturous ordeal\", as the writers defended their artistic vision and did not want some of the changes to be made.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/109501-it-had-to-show-how-we-rip-each-other-apart-galder-gaztelu-urrutia-on-his-vertical-class-warfare-netflix-dystopia-the-platform/#.Xonnzux4Hag |title=\"It Had to Show How We Rip Each Other Apart\u201d: Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia on His Vertical Class-Warfare Netflix Dystopia The Platform |last= Aguilar|first=Carlos |date= 3 April 2020| website= filmmakermagazine.com|publisher=Filmmaker |access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe cement prison cells were built for the production in a Red Cross facility in a port in Bilbao. The director asked for cells that looked \"economical, robust, [and] impregnable\", which emphasized a sense of architectural and engineering proportion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cineuropa.org/en/interview/379967 |title=Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia \u2022 Director of The Platform |last= Rivera|first= Alfonso|date=16 October 2020 |website= cineuropa.org|publisher= Cineuropa|access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> Only two tiers of concrete cells were built; the appearance of many tiers of cells extending above and below each cell (visible from the hole in the center of each cell) was added in post-production using special effects.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cineuropa.org/en/interview/379967 |title=Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia \u2022 Director of The Platform |last= Rivera|first= Alfonso|date=16 October 2020 |website= cineuropa.org|publisher= Cineuropa|access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> The director says the vertical tower of cells \"...represents the dehumanized coldness of the Vertical Self-Management Center.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/109501-it-had-to-show-how-we-rip-each-other-apart-galder-gaztelu-urrutia-on-his-vertical-class-warfare-netflix-dystopia-the-platform/#.Xonnzux4Hag |title=\"It Had to Show How We Rip Each Other Apart\u201d: Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia on His Vertical Class-Warfare Netflix Dystopia The Platform |last= Aguilar|first=Carlos |date= 3 April 2020| website= filmmakermagazine.com|publisher=Filmmaker |access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe director states that the film's lavish \"food was treated as another character in the story, one that is aesthetically antagonistic to the architecture of the prison.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/109501-it-had-to-show-how-we-rip-each-other-apart-galder-gaztelu-urrutia-on-his-vertical-class-warfare-netflix-dystopia-the-platform/#.Xonnzux4Hag |title=\"It Had to Show How We Rip Each Other Apart\u201d: Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia on His Vertical Class-Warfare Netflix Dystopia The Platform |last= Aguilar|first=Carlos |date= 3 April 2020| website= filmmakermagazine.com|publisher=Filmmaker |access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> The luxurious displays of gourmet food were presented on \"[[Versailles]]-worthy tableware\" to depict \"...excessive, almost erotic, opulent desire\" that is eventually \"desecrated\" once the near-empty platform reaches the [[abjection|abject]], starving inmates on the lower levels.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/109501-it-had-to-show-how-we-rip-each-other-apart-galder-gaztelu-urrutia-on-his-vertical-class-warfare-netflix-dystopia-the-platform/#.Xonnzux4Hag |title=\"It Had to Show How We Rip Each Other Apart\u201d: Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia on His Vertical Class-Warfare Netflix Dystopia The Platform |last= Aguilar|first=Carlos |date= 3 April 2020| website= filmmakermagazine.com|publisher=Filmmaker |access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe director acknowledges that the film can be difficult to watch, but he says the purpose of this approach is to generate discussion and debate by viewers about the political messages.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cineuropa.org/en/interview/379967 |title=Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia \u2022 Director of The Platform |last= Rivera|first= Alfonso|date=16 October 2020 |website= cineuropa.org|publisher= Cineuropa|access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> When asked about the film's brutal violence and cannibalism, the director said the prison's \"...hole is a reflection of our society, [so] it couldn\u2019t hide the violence. It had to show how we rip each other apart\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/109501-it-had-to-show-how-we-rip-each-other-apart-galder-gaztelu-urrutia-on-his-vertical-class-warfare-netflix-dystopia-the-platform/#.Xonnzux4Hag |title=\"It Had to Show How We Rip Each Other Apart\u201d: Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia on His Vertical Class-Warfare Netflix Dystopia The Platform |last= Aguilar|first=Carlos |date= 3 April 2020| website= filmmakermagazine.com|publisher=Filmmaker |access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> \n\nThe film uses two actors who are cast [[against type]]; [[Iv\u00e1n Massagu\u00e9]] and [[Antonia San Juan]], who are known for their comedic roles, were chosen to lighten the film's weighty subject by adding \"...humour, irony and surrealism\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cineuropa.org/en/interview/379967 |title=Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia \u2022 Director of The Platform |last= Rivera|first= Alfonso|date=16 October 2020 |website= cineuropa.org|publisher= Cineuropa|access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> The film was shot chronologically, as the main actor Iv\u00e1n had to  lose 12 kilos over the six-week shoot to show his physical deterioration.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/109501-it-had-to-show-how-we-rip-each-other-apart-galder-gaztelu-urrutia-on-his-vertical-class-warfare-netflix-dystopia-the-platform/#.Xonnzux4Hag |title=\"It Had to Show How We Rip Each Other Apart\u201d: Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia on His Vertical Class-Warfare Netflix Dystopia The Platform |last= Aguilar|first=Carlos |date= 3 April 2020| website= filmmakermagazine.com|publisher=Filmmaker |access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Critical response==\nOn the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 83% based on 52 reviews with an average rating of 7.43/10. The website's critics consensus reads: \"While it may feel muddled at times, ''The Platform'' is an inventive and captivating dystopian thriller.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Platform (El Hoyo) (2019)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_platform|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Norman Wilner of ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'' correctly predicted that the film would win the People's Choice Award, giving it a five-N rating and writing that the film \"has everything: low comedy, political allegory, left-field twists, crowd-pleasing surprises, spectacular violence, sadism, altruism and yet more spectacular violence, all wrapped up in a high-concept horror film that moves the premise of ''[[Cube (film)|Cube]]'' into a merciless vertical structure. It\u2019s grotesque and compelling, like [[grindhouse]] [Luis] [[Luis Bu\u00f1uel|Bu\u00f1uel]]. And it never blinks.\"<ref>Norman Wilner, [https://nowtoronto.com/movies/tiff2019/tiff-review-the-platform-galder-gaztelu-urrutia/ \"TIFF review: The Platform (El Hoyo)\"]. ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'', 1 September 2019.</ref>\n\nAmy Nicholson of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote that \"the film\u2019s minimalist fury feels like the plays of [[Samuel Beckett]]. Massagu\u00e9 and Eguileor are up to being in a zesty ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' (''Waiting for Gateau''). And Eguileor's nasty, delightful, occasionally tender performance feels like an audition to play a [[James Bond|Bond]] villain, or perhaps the Spanish resurrection of [[Hannibal Lecter]].\"<ref name=nicholson/>\n\n== Socio-economical game-theory example ==\nThere is a well-known socio-economical concept called \"[[Tragedy of the commons|Tragedy of the Commons]]\" related to the plot of this movie, in which players (664 players in this particular movie) are using a shared renewable resource, in an unregulated way. they can choose rational strategies by the help of which, the resource can serve all participants forever. However, Human psychological and social characteristics and excessive greed of every player, ends up using the resource in a non-sustainable way and sometimes more than needed and finally system crashes, people die starving, and Platform can't operate. However, the first time a regulation is established by two players in the movie, platform starts to serve all the players and this scenario can become a representation of maturity of the whole population.<ref>{{Citation|title=Tragedy of the commons|date=2020-04-09|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tragedy_of_the_commons&oldid=949871748|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|film}}\n* {{IMDb title|8228288}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|the_platform}}\n{{TIFF People's Choice Midnight Madness}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Platform, The}}\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:Films about cannibalism]]\n[[Category:Films about food and drink]]\n[[Category:Films set in prison]]\n[[Category:Spanish films]]\n[[Category:Spanish science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language Netflix original films]]\n[[Category:Dystopian films]]\n[[Category:Fictional buildings and structures]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|2019 Spanish science fiction film by Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Platform\n| film name      = ''El Valiente''\n| image          = The Platform poster.jpg\n| caption        = Promotional release poster\n| director       = [[Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n*David Desola\n*Pedro Rivero\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Iv\u00e1n Massagu\u00e9]]\n*Zorion Eguileor\n*[[Antonia San Juan]]\n*[[Emilio Buale Coka]]\n*Alexandra Masangkay\n}}\n| music          = Aranzazu Calleja\n| cinematography = Jon D. Dom\u00ednguez\n| editing        = Haritz Zubillaga<br />Elena Ruiz\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n*Basque Films\n*Mr. Miyagi Films\n*Plataforma La Pel\u00edcula A.I.E\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Netflix]]\n| released       = {{Nowrap|{{film date|2019|09|06|df=y|[[2019 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2020|03|20|Netflix}}}}\n| runtime        = 94 minutes\n| country        = Spain\n| language       = Spanish\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''The Platform''''' ({{lang-es|El hoyo}}, {{Translation|''The Hole''}}) is a Spanish [[science fiction film|science fiction]] [[horror film|horror]]-[[thriller film|thriller]] film, directed by [[Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia]] and released in 2019.<ref name=nicholson>Amy Nicholson, [https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/the-platform-review-1203330373/ \"Toronto Film Review: 'The Platform'\"]. ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', 10 September 2019.</ref> The film is set in a large, tower-style \"Vertical Self-Management Center\" where the residents, who are periodically switched at random between its 300+ floors, are fed by a platform, initially filled with food, that gradually descends through the levels. It is a system bound to cause conflict, as inmates at the top levels can eat as much as they can, leaving increasingly little for those below.<ref name=nicholson/>\n\nThe film's cast includes [[Iv\u00e1n Massagu\u00e9]], [[Antonia San Juan]], Zorion Eguileor, [[Emilio Buale Coka]] and Alexandra Masangkay.<ref name=nicholson/>\n\nThe film premiered at the [[2019 Toronto International Film Festival]], where it won the [[Toronto International Film Festival People's Choice Award: Midnight Madness|People's Choice Award for Midnight Madness]].<ref>Jessica Wong, [https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/tiff19-awards-1.5284085 \"TIFF 2019: Jojo Rabbit captures TIFF People's Choice Award\"]. [[CBC News]], 15 September 2019.</ref> At TIFF, the film also secured a worldwide streaming deal with [[Netflix]].<ref>Jeremy Kay, [https://www.screendaily.com/news/netflix-takes-world-on-tiff-midnight-madness-hit-the-platform/5142804.article \"Netflix takes world on TIFF Midnight Madness hit 'The Platform'\"]. ''[[Screen Daily]]'', 10 September 2019.</ref> It was released on the streaming service on 20 March 2020.\n\n==Plot==\nGoreng awakes in a concrete cell marked with the number 48. His roommate, Trimagasi, explains that they are in a tower-style facility in which food is delivered via a platform that travels from the top, stopping for a fixed period on each floor. Those on lower levels are able to eat only what those at the top leave them, and they cannot hoard food (the cell is heated or cooled to fatal levels if food is kept). Every month, people are randomly reassigned to a new level. Each resident is allowed to bring one item in with them, Goreng choosing a copy of ''[[Don Quixote]]'', and Trimagasi a self-sharpening knife called the Samurai Plus. \n\nOne day, a bloodied woman named Miharu rides down on the platform, and Trimagasi explains that she descends the pit every month in search of her child. Goreng sees her being attacked by the two people on the level below, and he considers jumping down to help her, but she kills them both and rides the platform down again.\n\nAs they talk, it is revealed that Goreng volunteered to spend six months in the \"Vertical Self-Management Center\" in exchange for a diploma, and Trimagasi is serving a year-long sentence for manslaughter. Over the month, they become friendly, but on the day of the room shuffle, Goreng wakes up tied to the bed. They have been reassigned to level 171, where the platform is expected to be empty of food when it arrives. Trimagasi explains that he plans to cut strips of Goreng's flesh to sustain them both, but only in moderate amounts so he doesn't bleed out. On the eighth day, Trimagasi cuts into Goreng's leg but is attacked by Miharu as she comes down the platform. She frees Goreng and he kills Trimagasi. Miharu cuts some of Trimagasi's flesh, feeding Goreng and eating some herself before continuing down.\n\nThe following month, Goreng awakes on level 33 with a woman, Imoguiri, as a cellmate. The only thing she brought with her was her dog. Goreng recognizes her as the Administration official who interviewed him before sending him to the cells. She tells Goreng that she believes there are 200 floors. She says she was unaware of the horrible conditions and volunteered to try to fix things when she was diagnosed with terminal cancer. Imoguiri rations her food and attempts to convince those below to do so as well, but they ignore her until Goreng threatens to defecate in their food.\n\nGoreng encounters Miharu once again as she rides down on the platform but she appears critically injured, presumably from being in a fight on the higher levels. Goreng and Imoguiri grab her off the platform and tend to her wounds. Goreng explains to Imoguiri about Miharu's search for her child, but Imoguiri says nobody under the age of 16 is allowed into the facility and says Miharu entered alone. \n\nGoreng awakens to see Miharu and Imoguiri in a standoff, as Miharu has eaten Imoguiri's dog.  Goreng awakens the following month on level 202 and finds that Imoguiri has hanged herself. Goreng eats her flesh to survive, experiencing hallucinations of her and Trimagasi instructing him to do so. He then awakens the following month on level 6. His roommate, Baharat, attempts to climb up through the upper level with the help of those above using a rope he brought into the pit. The couple living on the level above first help him, but end up defecating in his face, and pushing him back down. Estimating that there are around 250 levels, Goreng makes a plan to ride the platform down, rationing the food so all get a share, and convinces Baharat to go with him.\n\nAs they descend, they hand out portions to the prisoners, attacking those who refuse to cooperate. Going down, they encounter Miharu fighting two other residents and try to help her, but she is killed, and both men are injured. Goreng and Baharat continue to descend, eventually passing level 250 and reaching level 333 where the platform stops. Goreng notices a child hiding under the bed, and assumes it is Miharu's son. He gets off the platform, followed hesitantly by Baharat, only to have the platform continue downward, leaving them behind. They then discover the child is actually a girl, who turns out to be Miharu's  daughter. Despite Baharat's reluctance, they feed her an untouched [[panna cotta]] they had been saving as a \"message\" for the Administrators at the top. \n\nGoreng passes out and dreams of Baharat telling him that \"the girl is the message.\" The next day, Goreng finds Baharat dead after succumbing to his injuries, and takes the child with him when the platform arrives; they descend to the bottom of the pit where he once again sees Trimagasi, who tells him that \"the message requires no bearer.\" Goreng gets off the platform and walks away with Trimagasi, both turning to watch as the girl is transported upwards.\n\n== Cast==\n[[File:El hoyo prentsaurrekoa rueda de prensa.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Cast and crew members at a press conference in October 2019.]]\n* [[Iv\u00e1n Massagu\u00e9]] as ''Goreng'', named after ''[[:wiktionary:goreng|gor\u00e8ng]]'', which means \"fried\" in Malay/Indonesian.\n* Zorion Eguileor ([[:eu:Zorion_Egileor|eu]]) as ''Trimagasi'', named after terima kasih, which stands for \"thank you\" in Malay/Indonesian language\n* [[Antonia San Juan]] as ''Imoguiri'', named after ''[[Imogiri]]'', a royal graveyard in Indonesia. \n* [[Emilio Buale Coka]] as ''Baharat'', named after ''[[baharat]]'', a spice blend used in Turkish and Greek cuisine.\n* Alexandra Masangkay as ''Miharu'' \n* Eric L. Goode as ''Sr. Brambang'', named after ''[[shallot|brambang]]'', a shallot.\n\n==Production==\nGalder Gaztelu-Urrutia says the film's key message is that \"...humanity will have to move towards the fair [[distribution of wealth]]\", with an exploration of the importance of individual initiative in driving political change that critiques both [[capitalism]] and \"[[Socialism|socialist systems]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cineuropa.org/en/interview/379967 |title=Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia \u2022 Director of The Platform |last= Rivera|first= Alfonso|date=16 October 2020 |website= cineuropa.org|publisher= Cineuropa|access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> The film script is based on a theatre script by [[David Desola]] and [[Pedro Rivero]], to which more action and physical elements were added to make it more suitable for a film.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cineuropa.org/en/interview/379967 |title=Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia \u2022 Director of The Platform |last= Rivera|first= Alfonso|date=16 October 2020 |website= cineuropa.org|publisher= Cineuropa|access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> \"Extensive\" rewriting was required to convert the unproduced theater script into a film script. The director said it was a \"torturous ordeal\", as the writers defended their artistic vision and did not want some of the changes to be made.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/109501-it-had-to-show-how-we-rip-each-other-apart-galder-gaztelu-urrutia-on-his-vertical-class-warfare-netflix-dystopia-the-platform/#.Xonnzux4Hag |title=\"It Had to Show How We Rip Each Other Apart\u201d: Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia on His Vertical Class-Warfare Netflix Dystopia The Platform |last= Aguilar|first=Carlos |date= 3 April 2020| website= filmmakermagazine.com|publisher=Filmmaker |access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe cement prison cells were built for the production in a Red Cross facility in a port in Bilbao. The director asked for cells that looked \"economical, robust, [and] impregnable\", which emphasized a sense of architectural and engineering proportion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cineuropa.org/en/interview/379967 |title=Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia \u2022 Director of The Platform |last= Rivera|first= Alfonso|date=16 October 2020 |website= cineuropa.org|publisher= Cineuropa|access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> Only two tiers of concrete cells were built; the appearance of many tiers of cells extending above and below each cell (visible from the hole in the center of each cell) was added in post-production using special effects.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cineuropa.org/en/interview/379967 |title=Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia \u2022 Director of The Platform |last= Rivera|first= Alfonso|date=16 October 2020 |website= cineuropa.org|publisher= Cineuropa|access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> The director says the vertical tower of cells \"...represents the dehumanized coldness of the Vertical Self-Management Center.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/109501-it-had-to-show-how-we-rip-each-other-apart-galder-gaztelu-urrutia-on-his-vertical-class-warfare-netflix-dystopia-the-platform/#.Xonnzux4Hag |title=\"It Had to Show How We Rip Each Other Apart\u201d: Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia on His Vertical Class-Warfare Netflix Dystopia The Platform |last= Aguilar|first=Carlos |date= 3 April 2020| website= filmmakermagazine.com|publisher=Filmmaker |access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe director states that the film's lavish \"food was treated as another character in the story, one that is aesthetically antagonistic to the architecture of the prison.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/109501-it-had-to-show-how-we-rip-each-other-apart-galder-gaztelu-urrutia-on-his-vertical-class-warfare-netflix-dystopia-the-platform/#.Xonnzux4Hag |title=\"It Had to Show How We Rip Each Other Apart\u201d: Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia on His Vertical Class-Warfare Netflix Dystopia The Platform |last= Aguilar|first=Carlos |date= 3 April 2020| website= filmmakermagazine.com|publisher=Filmmaker |access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> The luxurious displays of gourmet food were presented on \"[[Versailles]]-worthy tableware\" to depict \"...excessive, almost erotic, opulent desire\" that is eventually \"desecrated\" once the near-empty platform reaches the [[abjection|abject]], starving inmates on the lower levels.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/109501-it-had-to-show-how-we-rip-each-other-apart-galder-gaztelu-urrutia-on-his-vertical-class-warfare-netflix-dystopia-the-platform/#.Xonnzux4Hag |title=\"It Had to Show How We Rip Each Other Apart\u201d: Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia on His Vertical Class-Warfare Netflix Dystopia The Platform |last= Aguilar|first=Carlos |date= 3 April 2020| website= filmmakermagazine.com|publisher=Filmmaker |access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe director acknowledges that the film can be difficult to watch, but he says the purpose of this approach is to generate discussion and debate by viewers about the political messages.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cineuropa.org/en/interview/379967 |title=Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia \u2022 Director of The Platform |last= Rivera|first= Alfonso|date=16 October 2020 |website= cineuropa.org|publisher= Cineuropa|access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> When asked about the film's brutal violence and cannibalism, the director said the prison's \"...hole is a reflection of our society, [so] it couldn\u2019t hide the violence. It had to show how we rip each other apart\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/109501-it-had-to-show-how-we-rip-each-other-apart-galder-gaztelu-urrutia-on-his-vertical-class-warfare-netflix-dystopia-the-platform/#.Xonnzux4Hag |title=\"It Had to Show How We Rip Each Other Apart\u201d: Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia on His Vertical Class-Warfare Netflix Dystopia The Platform |last= Aguilar|first=Carlos |date= 3 April 2020| website= filmmakermagazine.com|publisher=Filmmaker |access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> \n\nThe film uses two actors who are cast [[against type]]; [[Iv\u00e1n Massagu\u00e9]] and [[Antonia San Juan]], who are known for their comedic roles, were chosen to lighten the film's weighty subject by adding \"...humour, irony and surrealism\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cineuropa.org/en/interview/379967 |title=Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia \u2022 Director of The Platform |last= Rivera|first= Alfonso|date=16 October 2020 |website= cineuropa.org|publisher= Cineuropa|access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref> The film was shot chronologically, as the main actor Iv\u00e1n had to  lose 12 kilos over the six-week shoot to show his physical deterioration.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/109501-it-had-to-show-how-we-rip-each-other-apart-galder-gaztelu-urrutia-on-his-vertical-class-warfare-netflix-dystopia-the-platform/#.Xonnzux4Hag |title=\"It Had to Show How We Rip Each Other Apart\u201d: Galder Gaztelu-Urrutia on His Vertical Class-Warfare Netflix Dystopia The Platform |last= Aguilar|first=Carlos |date= 3 April 2020| website= filmmakermagazine.com|publisher=Filmmaker |access-date=5 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Critical response==\nOn the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 83% based on 52 reviews with an average rating of 7.43/10. The website's critics consensus reads: \"While it may feel muddled at times, ''The Platform'' is an inventive and captivating dystopian thriller.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Platform (El Hoyo) (2019)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_platform|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Norman Wilner of ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'' correctly predicted that the film would win the People's Choice Award, giving it a five-N rating and writing that the film \"has everything: low comedy, political allegory, left-field twists, crowd-pleasing surprises, spectacular violence, sadism, altruism and yet more spectacular violence, all wrapped up in a high-concept horror film that moves the premise of ''[[Cube (film)|Cube]]'' into a merciless vertical structure. It\u2019s grotesque and compelling, like [[grindhouse]] [Luis] [[Luis Bu\u00f1uel|Bu\u00f1uel]]. And it never blinks.\"<ref>Norman Wilner, [https://nowtoronto.com/movies/tiff2019/tiff-review-the-platform-galder-gaztelu-urrutia/ \"TIFF review: The Platform (El Hoyo)\"]. ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'', 1 September 2019.</ref>\n\nAmy Nicholson of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote that \"the film\u2019s minimalist fury feels like the plays of [[Samuel Beckett]]. Massagu\u00e9 and Eguileor are up to being in a zesty ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' (''Waiting for Gateau''). And Eguileor's nasty, delightful, occasionally tender performance feels like an audition to play a [[James Bond|Bond]] villain, or perhaps the Spanish resurrection of [[Hannibal Lecter]].\"<ref name=nicholson/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|film}}\n* {{IMDb title|8228288}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|the_platform}}\n{{TIFF People's Choice Midnight Madness}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Platform, The}}\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:Films about cannibalism]]\n[[Category:Films about food and drink]]\n[[Category:Films set in prison]]\n[[Category:Spanish films]]\n[[Category:Spanish science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language Netflix original films]]\n[[Category:Dystopian films]]\n[[Category:Fictional buildings and structures]]\n", "name_user": "HKEsfahani", "label": "safe", "comment": "I've just added a simple concept of a game-theory example that can be extracted of the plot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Platform_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Eros Pagni", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image        = Eros Pagni and Lina Volonghi.jpg\n|caption      = Pagni (left) with [[Lina Volonghi]] in 1973\n|name         = Eros Pagni\n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1939|8|28|df=yes}}\n|birth_place  = [[La Spezia]], Italy\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  =\n|occupation   = Actor, voice actor \n|yearsactive  = 1964-present\n}}\n'''Eros Pagni''' (born 28 August 1939) is an Italian actor and voice actor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/voci/vociepag.htm |title=Eros Pagni's dubbing contributions|publisher=Antoniogenna.net |date= |accessdate= 19 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[La Spezia]], at the age of 17, Pagni started attending the [[Accademia Nazionale di Arte Drammatica Silvio D'Amico|Silvio d'Amico National Academy of Dramatic Arts]] in [[Rome]] and then went back to [[Genoa]] and played roles in works by [[William Shakespeare]], [[Moli\u00e8re]], [[Eugene O'Neill]], [[Luigi Pirandello]] and more.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mymovies.it/biografia/?a=3198 |title=Eros Pagni |author= |publisher=MYmovies |date= |accessdate= 14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs a film actor, Pagni has appeared in 34 films since 1964. He is well known for his role in [[Dario Argento]]'s ''[[Deep Red]]'' and for his collaboration with [[Lina Wertm\u00fcller]] in movies like ''[[Love and Anarchy]]'', ''[[Swept Away (1974 film)|Swept Away]]'' and ''[[All Screwed Up]]''.\n\nHe received with all the cast of [[Ettore Scola]]'s ''[[The Dinner (1998 film)|The Dinner]]'' the [[Nastro d'Argento for Best Supporting Actor|Nastro d'Argento Award for Best Supporting Actor]].\n\nOccasionally, Pagni is also a voice actor. He is notable for having dubbed actors like [[Aldo Ray]] in ''[[The Green Berets (film)|The Green Berets]]'', [[R. Lee Ermey]] in ''[[Full Metal Jacket]]'' and [[Christopher Lee]] in ''[[Gremlins 2: The New Batch]]'' and animated characters such as [[Judge Claude Frollo]] from ''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame (1996 film)|The Hunchback of Notre Dame]]'' and [[List of Kung Fu Panda characters#Master Shifu|Master Shifu]] in the ''[[Kung Fu Panda (franchise)|Kung Fu Panda]]'' film series.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Pleasant Nights]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Il generale dorme in piedi]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Love and Anarchy]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[Swept Away (1974 film)|Swept Away]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[All Screwed Up]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Processo per direttissima]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Deep Red]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Soldier of Fortune (1976 film)|Soldier of Fortune]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[I nuovi mostri]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[Goodnight, Ladies and Gentlemen]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[Liquirizia]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Il malato immaginario|Hypochondriac]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Odd Squad (film)|Odd Squad]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[Grog (film)|Grog]]'' (1982)\n* ''[[Flirt (1983 film)|Flirt]]'' (1983)\t\n* ''[[Teresa (1987 film)|Teresa]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Red American]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[The Storm Is Coming]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[The Dinner (1998 film)|The Dinner]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Love Returns]]'' (2004)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Dubbing roles==\n===Animation===\n*[[Claude Frollo]] in ''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame (1996 film)|The Hunchback of Notre Dame]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/film/ilgobbodinotredame.htm |title=The Hunchback of Notre Dame Italian voice cast|publisher=Antoniogenna.net |date= |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Master Shifu in ''[[Kung Fu Panda]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/film1/kungfupanda.htm |title=Kung Fu Panda Italian voice cast|publisher=Antoniogenna.net |date= |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Master Shifu in ''[[Kung Fu Panda 2]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/film1/kungfupanda2.htm |title=Kung Fu Panda 2 Italian voice cast|publisher=Antoniogenna.net |date= |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Master Shifu in ''[[Kung Fu Panda 3]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/film1/kungfupanda3.htm |title=Kung Fu Panda 3 Italian voice cast|publisher=Antoniogenna.net |date= |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Tzekel-Kan in ''[[The Road to El Dorado]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/film1/lastradapereldorado.htm |title=The Road to El Dorado Italian voice cast|publisher=Antoniogenna.net |date= |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Live action===\n*Gunnery Sergeant Hartman in ''[[Full Metal Jacket]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/film/fullmetaljacket.htm |title=Full Metal Jacket Italian voice cast|publisher=Antoniogenna.net |date= |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n*The Governor in ''[[A Violent Life]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/film1/unavitascellerata.htm |title=A Violent Life Italian voice cast|publisher=Antoniogenna.net |date= |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Doctor Catheter in ''[[Gremlins 2: The New Batch]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/film/gremlins2.htm |title=Gremlins 2: The New Batch Italian voice cast|publisher=Antoniogenna.net |date= |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Ma\u00eetre Martin in ''Les Rois maudits''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/mini/lamaledizdeitemplari.htm |title=Les rois maudits Italian voice cast|publisher=Antoniogenna.net |date= |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Ezra Goldman in ''[[Ray Donovan]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/telefilm/raydonovan.htm |title=Ray Donovan Italian voice cast|publisher=Antoniogenna.net |date= |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat-inline}}\n*{{IMDB name|0656521|Eros Pagni}}\n*{{Amg name|148601|Eros Pagni}}\n\n{{Nastro d'Argento Best supporting Actor |state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pagni, Eros}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from La Spezia]]\n[[Category:Italian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Italian male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Italian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Italian male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Accademia Nazionale di Arte Drammatica Silvio D'Amico alumni]]\n[[Category:Nastro d'Argento winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image        = Eros Pagni and Lina Volonghi.jpg\n|caption      = Pagni (left) with [[Lina Volonghi]] in 1973\n|name         = Eros Pagni\n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1939|8|28|df=yes}}\n|birth_place  = [[La Spezia]], Italy\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  =\n|occupation   = Actor, voice actor \n|yearsactive  = 1964-present\n}}\n'''Eros Pagni''' (born 28 August 1939) is an Italian actor and voice actor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/voci/vociepag.htm |title=Eros Pagni's dubbing contributions|publisher=Antoniogenna.net |date= |accessdate= 19 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[La Spezia]], at the age of 17, Pagni started attending the [[Accademia Nazionale di Arte Drammatica Silvio D'Amico|Silvio d'Amico National Academy of Dramatic Arts]] in [[Rome]] and then went back to [[Genoa]] and played roles in works by [[William Shakespeare]], [[Moli\u00e8re]], [[Eugene O'Neill]], [[Luigi Pirandello]] and more.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mymovies.it/biografia/?a=3198 |title=Eros Pagni |author= |publisher=MYmovies |date= |accessdate= 14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs a film actor, Pagni has appeared in 34 films since 1964. He is well known for his role in [[Dario Argento]]'s ''[[Deep Red]]'' and for his collaboration with [[Lina Wertm\u00fcller]] in movies like ''[[Love and Anarchy]]'', ''[[Swept Away (1974 film)|Swept Away]]'' and ''[[All Screwed Up]]''.\n\nHe received with all the cast of [[Ettore Scola]]'s ''[[The Dinner (1998 film)|The Dinner]]'' the [[Nastro d'Argento for Best Supporting Actor|Nastro d'Argento Award for Best Supporting Actor]].\n\nOccasionally, Pagni is also a voice actor. He is notable for having dubbed actors like [[Aldo Ray]] in ''[[The Green Berets (film)|The Green Berets]]'', [[R. Lee Ermey]] in ''[[Full Metal Jacket]]'' and [[Christopher Lee]] in ''[[Gremlins 2: The New Batch]]'' and animated characters such as [[Judge Claude Frollo]] from ''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame (1996 film)|The Hunchback of Notre Dame]]'' and [[List of Kung Fu Panda characters#Master Shifu|Master Shifu]] in the ''[[Kung Fu Panda (franchise)|Kung Fu Panda]]'' film series.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Pleasant Nights]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Il generale dorme in piedi]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Love and Anarchy]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[Swept Away (1974 film)|Swept Away]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[All Screwed Up]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Processo per direttissima]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Deep Red]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Soldier of Fortune (1976 film)|Soldier of Fortune]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[I nuovi mostri]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[Goodnight, Ladies and Gentlemen]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[Liquirizia]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Il malato immaginario|Hypochondriac]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Odd Squad (film)|Odd Squad]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[Grog (film)|Grog]]'' (1982)\n* ''[[Flirt (1983 film)|Flirt]]'' (1983)\t\n* ''[[Teresa (1987 film)|Teresa]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Red American]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[The Storm Is Coming]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[The Dinner (1998 film)|The Dinner]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Love Returns]]'' (2004)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Dubbing roles==\n===Animation===\n*[[Claude Frollo]] in ''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame (1996 film)|The Hunchback of Notre Dame]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/film/ilgobbodinotredame.htm |title=The Hunchback of Notre Dame Italian voice cast|publisher=Antoniogenna.net |date= |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n*Master Shifu in ''[[Kung Fu Panda]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antoniogenna.net/doppiaggio/film1/kungfupanda.htm